      <h2>Abstract</h2>
<p>This manuscript examines price behavior relative to five anchored Volume Weighted Average Price (VWAP) distributions initiated at statistically significant order flow extremes on May 14 (Green), July 7 (Orange), September 23 (Yellow), November 28 (Light Blue), and January 13 (Pink). By maintaining these anchors concurrently at identical scale, a stratified model of inventory control emerges. Anchored VWAP distributions, when initiated at structurally meaningful flow events, approximate evolving cost bases of dominant market participants. The central finding is that regime transitions are not defined by isolated breakdowns but by sequential propagation of sustained acceptance failure into progressively older anchored layers. The framework presented herein interprets market structure as layered inventory persistence rather than linear trend progression and provides a documented snapshot of current regime dynamics as of February 18.</p>
<h2>1. Introduction</h2>
<p>Price is the visible output of inventory transfer. Every transaction represents a shift in risk ownership between participants operating under different constraints, horizons, and motivations. While trend analysis and momentum measures describe directional movement, they do not explicitly account for the persistence of inventory once it has been transferred under stress.</p>
<p>Periods of statistically abnormal order flow often coincide with structural inflection points. During such events, aggressive participation overwhelms resting liquidity, imbalance widens, and inventory is transferred at scale. These episodes are not merely high-volume sessions; they represent moments in which positioning changes hands in a way that materially affects subsequent auction behavior.</p>
<p>If one anchors VWAP at these inflection points, the resulting distribution evolves as a cumulative representation of where business has transacted since that event. The anchored mean functions as a dynamic estimate of cohort cost basis. When multiple such anchors are layered chronologically, price can be interpreted not as a single trend line, but as migration between stacked cost bases.</p>
<p>This layered interpretation transforms structural analysis. Instead of asking whether price has broken a single reference, the more relevant inquiry becomes whether weakness has penetrated deeply enough to redefine which inventory cohort controls the auction.</p>
<h2>2. Methodological Considerations: Defining a Flow Extreme</h2>
<p>Anchoring VWAP at arbitrary swing highs or lows produces descriptive means but does not reliably capture structural inventory transfer. The validity of this framework depends on anchoring at moments characterized by measurable order flow imbalance.</p>
<p>A statistically significant flow extreme generally exhibits several characteristics:</p>
<h4>Aggressive Participation Surge</h4>
<p>A pronounced expansion in market orders relative to resting liquidity. This is typically observable as a spike in trade aggressiveness, where lifting of offers or hitting of bids occurs at a pace that exceeds typical auction rhythm.</p>
<h4>Liquidity Imbalance</h4>
<p>Depth on one side of the book either retreats or absorbs disproportionately. In retreat scenarios, liquidity pulls away and price moves rapidly. In absorption scenarios, large resting interest repeatedly replenishes while aggressive flow persists.</p>
<h4>Volatility Expansion</h4>
<p>True flow extremes coincide with abrupt range expansion. Price does not drift; it moves decisively, often completing structural rotations that alter positioning assumptions.</p>
<h4>Cohort Transfer Under Stress</h4>
<p>The defining feature of a structural flow extreme is not merely volume but the context in which volume trades. Inventory is transferred under pressure—late participants are forced to transact, while stronger participants absorb or initiate with conviction.</p>
<p>These events establish new cost bases that matter for weeks or months. Anchoring VWAP at these points captures the evolution of that cost basis without requiring direct visibility into individual participant balance sheets.</p>
<hr>
<h2>3. Anchored VWAP as an Evolving Inventory Axis</h2>
<p>An anchored VWAP beginning at time \(t_0\) is defined as:</p>
<p>$$\text{VWAP}_t = \frac{\sum_{i=t_0}^{t} P_i \, V_i}{\sum_{i=t_0}^{t} V_i}$$</p>
<p>When \(t_0\) corresponds to a flow extreme, this anchored mean represents the volume-weighted equilibrium of all transactions since that event. It is therefore a continuously updated approximation of cohort cost basis.</p>
<p>Price relative to this mean carries structural implications:</p>
<ul>
<li>Sustained trade above the mean implies the cohort remains structurally profitable.</li>
<li>Sustained trade below the mean implies cohort stress and potential redistribution.</li>
<li>Rapid rejection of excursions beyond ±2 standard deviations suggests responsive participation.</li>
<li>Persistent acceptance beyond historical dispersion patterns suggests expansion or decay.</li>
</ul>
<p>The distinction between a probe and acceptance is essential. A probe is a transient excursion that quickly reverts. Acceptance is characterized by repeated closes and time spent beyond the mean, often across multiple sessions, without immediate reclamation. Structural decay is inferred from acceptance, not probing.</p>
