<h2>4. May 14 (Green): Structural Foundation</h2>
<p>The May 14 anchor represents the deepest layer within the current hierarchy. Its dispersion envelope is broad, reflecting both the magnitude of the initiating flow event and the extended duration of participation that followed.</p>
<p>Over time, the anchored mean developed a persistent upward slope. This slope did not accelerate abruptly; it evolved gradually, suggesting controlled accumulation rather than reactive short covering. The distribution matured through multiple volatility cycles, yet sustained acceptance below the mean failed to materialize.</p>
<p>Lower deviation penetrations were repeatedly absorbed. Price rotated back toward equilibrium with consistency. This pattern implies that the cohort formed at this event possessed both capital resilience and conviction.</p>
<p>Because of its temporal depth and persistence, the May anchor functions as structural bedrock. Tactical breakdowns in more recent anchors have not materially threatened it. As long as price remains materially above this evolving mean and slope remains constructive, structural deterioration cannot be asserted.</p>
<hr>
<div class="figure">
  <img data-lightbox src="assets/img/july7-orange.png" data-full="assets/img/july7-orange.png" data-title="July 7 (Orange) — Reinforcement Within Macro Structure" alt="July 7 (Orange) — Reinforcement Within Macro Structure">
