</div>
<h2>8. January 13 (Pink): Redistribution and Short-Cycle Conflict</h2>
<p>The January 13 anchor is the most reactive layer in the hierarchy. Its dispersion expanded rapidly following formation and slope flattened earlier than prior anchors. Sigma penetrations have occurred with greater frequency and less containment.</p>
<p>Frequent crossings of the anchored mean indicate redistribution rather than consolidation. The Pink layer reflects active positioning conflict, not durable control.</p>
<p>This short-cycle anchor provides insight into immediate auction behavior but does not supersede deeper layers unless failure cascades downward. Its reactivity underscores the importance of distinguishing between tactical volatility and structural change.</p>
<hr>
<h2>9. Hierarchical Migration and Current Regime Status</h2>
<p>When all five anchors are observed concurrently, the hierarchy becomes explicit:</p>
<ul>
<li>Price remains materially above the May (Green) macro base.</li>
<li>July (Orange) reinforcement remains intact.</li>
<li>September (Yellow) equilibrium holds.</li>
<li>November (Light Blue) shows tactical decay.</li>
<li>January (Pink) reflects redistribution.</li>
</ul>
<p>The current configuration suggests compression within an intact macro regime. Tactical weakness has emerged, but deeper structural anchors have not been invalidated.</p>
<p>Migration between cost bases follows a sequential logic. Short-cycle cohorts fail first. Intermediate equilibrium layers absorb migration. Only when acceptance failure penetrates deeply into older anchors does regime transition occur.</p>
<p>As of February 18, such propagation has not occurred.</p>
<hr>
<h2>10. Conditions for Structural Transition</h2>
<p>Structural regime change would require sequential evidence:</p>
<ol>
<li>Sustained acceptance below the September (Yellow) mean.</li>
<li>Repeated failure to reclaim that mean on retests.</li>
<li>Flattening or inversion of slope in Yellow, followed by deterioration in Orange.</li>
<li>Persistent downside excursions beyond historical sigma behavior without responsive absorption.</li>
</ol>
<p>Absent these conditions, macro regime integrity remains defensible.</p>
<hr>
<h2>11. Conclusion</h2>
<p>Maintaining multiple anchored VWAP distributions from statistically significant flow extremes reveals a layered hierarchy of inventory persistence. Each anchor represents a cohort cost basis formed under stress. Structural interpretation emerges from observing how price interacts with these stacked layers.</p>
<ul>
<li>May 14 (Green) remains foundational.</li>
<li>July 7 (Orange) reinforces macro alignment.</li>
<li>September 23 (Yellow) stabilizes equilibrium.</li>
<li>November 28 (Light Blue) exhibits tactical decay.</li>
<li>January 13 (Pink) reflects short-cycle redistribution.</li>
</ul>
<p>The present regime state is consistent with tactical weakness and internal migration rather than confirmed macro transition. Control decays progressively, not instantaneously. Only when acceptance failure propagates into the deepest anchored layers can structural reversal be asserted.</p>
<p>This layered anchored VWAP framework therefore provides a coherent model of regime identification rooted in inventory persistence rather than superficial trend observation.</p>
<hr>
<h2>12. Sigma Interaction Statistics and Regime Decay Metrics</h2>
<p>While anchored VWAP layering provides a structural visual framework, its interpretive strength increases materially when dispersion behavior is quantified. The objective of sigma interaction statistics is not to over-engineer prediction, but to formalize observable regime characteristics: stretch, rejection, acceptance, and decay.</p>
<p>Each anchored distribution defines a time-evolving mean \(\mu_a(t)\) and standard deviation \(\sigma_a(t)\). Price can therefore be expressed in normalized form:</p>
<p>$$z_a(t) = \frac{P(t) - \mu_a(t)}{\sigma_a(t)}$$</p>
<p>This normalized distance allows comparison of dispersion behavior across anchors of different age, slope, and maturity.</p>
<h3>12.1 Touches, Visits, and Structural Interactions</h3>
<p>A distinction must be drawn between transient “touches” and meaningful structural interaction.</p>
<p>A simple touch occurs when \(|z_a(t)| \ge k\) for a chosen sigma level \(k\). However, single-bar excursions often reflect liquidity sweeps rather than structural stress.</p>
<p>A more meaningful construct is the concept of a visit. A visit begins when price first crosses beyond a sigma threshold \(k\) and ends when it returns inside that threshold. This converts isolated prints into discrete interaction episodes.</p>
<p>For each anchor and sigma level, the following can be measured:</p>
<ul>
<li>Number of visits \(N_a(k)\)</li>
<li>Average visit duration</li>
<li>Maximum visit duration</li>
</ul>
<p>Visit duration is particularly informative. Mature regimes tend to exhibit short-lived outer-band visits followed by mean reversion. Prolonged duration suggests imbalance persistence.</p>
<h3>12.2 Rejection Rate vs Acceptance Rate</h3>
<p>The most informative statistic for regime health is the ratio of rejections to acceptances at outer bands.</p>
<p>A rejection event occurs when price crosses beyond \(k\) sigma but returns inside the threshold within a predefined horizon \(H\), typically within several sessions.</p>
<p>An acceptance event occurs when price remains beyond \(k\) sigma for a sustained duration or repeatedly closes beyond that threshold.</p>
<p>For each anchor:</p>
<p>$$R_a(k) = \frac{\text{Rejections at }k}{\text{Total visits to }k}$$</p>
<p>$$A_a(k) = \frac{\text{Acceptances at }k}{\text{Total visits to }k}$$</p>
<p>Healthy regimes are characterized by high rejection rates at ±2 and ±2.5 sigma, particularly on the downside in upward regimes. Rising acceptance rates, especially below the mean, indicate cohort stress and emerging decay.</p>
<p>In the context of the November 28 anchor, the recent multi-session acceptance below its mean represents a measurable increase in acceptance frequency relative to prior history. The structural importance of that shift lies not in the mere crossing of the mean, but in the persistence of acceptance.</p>
<h3>12.3 Return-to-Mean Time</h3>
<p>Another informative metric is the expected time required for price to revert from a given sigma level back to the mean zone. Define the mean zone as a small neighborhood around zero, such as \(|z_a(t)| \le 0.25\).</p>
<p>For each visit beyond \(k\), compute the number of bars required to re-enter the mean zone. The average of these values defines the return-to-mean time \(\text{TMR}_a(k)\).</p>
<p>Short return times imply strong mean gravity and responsive participation. Increasing return times suggest weakening gravitational pull and potential structural transition.</p>
<p>In practice, a regime that previously reverted from -2 sigma in one to two sessions but now requires five to seven sessions is exhibiting measurable decay.</p>
<h3>12.4 Mean Slope and Dispersion Evolution</h3>
<p>Sigma interaction statistics should not be interpreted in isolation from slope dynamics.</p>
<p>The slope of the anchored mean provides context:</p>
<ul>
<li>Positive and stable slope with high rejection rates suggests persistent trend control.</li>
<li>Flattening slope combined with rising downside acceptance suggests redistribution.</li>
<li>Inversion of slope combined with persistent downside acceptance indicates structural transition.</li>
</ul>
<p>Dispersion envelope expansion or contraction also carries meaning:</p>
<ul>
<li>Expanding dispersion following sustained acceptance implies structural re-pricing.</li>
<li>Contracting dispersion with oscillation implies equilibrium.</li>
</ul>
<h3>12.5 Dominant Anchor Share of Time</h3>
<p>In a layered system, it is instructive to measure which anchored mean price orbits most closely at any given time. For each time interval, identify the anchor for which \(|z_a(t)|\) is smallest. The proportion of time that price spends closest to a given anchor defines its dominance share.</p>
<p>An increasing dominance share for a deeper anchor during tactical decay suggests migration rather than collapse. A sustained shift in dominance from a newer anchor to an older anchor formalizes the concept of regime migration.</p>
<h3>12.6 Cohort Health as a Composite Measure</h3>
<p>The above metrics can be synthesized into a qualitative health assessment for each anchor. A <strong>structurally healthy</strong> cohort exhibits:</p>
<ul>
<li>High rejection rate at outer bands</li>
<li>Low acceptance rate below the mean</li>
<li>Short return-to-mean time</li>
<li>Stable positive slope</li>
</ul>
<p>Conversely, <strong>cohort decay</strong> is defined by:</p>
<ul>
<li>Rising acceptance below the mean</li>
<li>Increasing visit duration at negative extremes</li>
<li>Lengthening return-to-mean time</li>
<li>Flattening or declining slope</li>
</ul>
<p>This framework quantifies what would otherwise be described qualitatively as “respecting the bands” or “losing control.”</p>
<h3>Structural Interpretation in the Current Hierarchy</h3>
<p>Applied to the present configuration:</p>
<ul>
<li>The May (Green) anchor exhibits persistent rejection behavior and stable slope, consistent with macro structural integrity.</li>
<li>The July (Orange) anchor remains nested and stable, indicating reinforcement rather than deterioration.</li>
<li>The September (Yellow) anchor maintains equilibrium characteristics, with limited sustained acceptance beyond historical dispersion norms.</li>
<li>The November (Light Blue) anchor shows a measurable shift toward acceptance below its mean and increasing visit duration, consistent with tactical decay.</li>
<li>The January (Pink) anchor displays high oscillation frequency and weaker rejection containment, characteristic of redistribution rather than durable control.</li>
</ul>
<p>Quantifying these interactions reinforces the visual interpretation: tactical stress has emerged, but deeper structural layers have not yet exhibited the statistical characteristics associated with regime transition.</p>
